column3: from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV from sklearn.model_selection import Randomize import time start_time=time.time() RF = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=-1,class_weight='balanced') parameters = { 'n_estimators' :[10, 100, 500, 1000],'max_depth': [10, 50, 100, 500, 1000]} clf = RandomizedSearchCV(RF,parameters, cv= 3, scoring='roc_auc',return_train_score=True) clf.fit(X_train, y_train) train_auc= clf.cv_results_['mean_train_score'] train_auc_std= clf.cv_results_['std_train_score'] cv_auc = clf.cv_results_['mean_test_score']  cv_auc_std= clf.cv_results_['std_test_score'] print("Execution time: " + str((time.time() - start_time)) + ' ms') train_auc = train_auc.reshape(5,2)  cv_auc = cv_auc.reshape(5,2) train_auc cv_auc plt.yticks(np.arange(4), [10, 100, 500, 1000]) plt.xticks(np.arange(5), [10, 50, 100, 500, 1000])

column2: Elastic cache redis performance in ecs
column3:
In our organization, we have been running a Node 6 application consisting of Nginx and application on Amazon EC2 instances. Usually at traffic it autoscales up to 14 m4.large EC2 instance and the response of time of the apis would be around 80 ms for 12k rpm load. We recently moved to AWS ECS, where each task had 2 containers (Nginx 
+ application) and also updated to node12. Now we have around 160 tasks (100 CPU unit for each Nginx + 100 CPU unit for application inside a task) running with 16 same m4.large instances. But the response time increased to 250 ms. In EC2 architecture which we used earlier took GET Elasticache Redis operation around 6ms whereas in ECS when load is high the Redis takes 70ms for the same operation. Please help to suggest some optimisation to get same EC2 performance.
